00:15:37,051 --> 00:15:40,726
Plus, they've got seemingly
unrestricted security clearance.

230
00:15:40,726 --> 00:15:44,969
Which means they'd have
the capability to erase
medical records if they wanted to.

231
00:15:44,962 --> 00:15:46,441
Exactly. Who runs this outfit?

232
00:15:46,440 --> 00:15:50,285
Institute director is a Dr Aaron
Copley. Yeah, I know his work.

233
00:15:50,277 --> 00:15:53,917
He's one of the most respected
research scientists in his field.

234
00:15:53,914 --> 00:15:56,075
Harvard graduate.
Did research at Cambridge.

235
00:15:56,072 --> 00:15:59,155
Last job, Harvard Professor
of Molecular Pharmacology.

236
00:15:59,148 --> 00:16:01,116
Came to the UK to set up the Pharm.

237
00:16:01,108 --> 00:16:02,985
Hmm, he's kinda handsome, too.

238
00:16:02,982 --> 00:16:04,904
D'you think he'll like visitors?

239
00:16:13,890 --> 00:16:16,336
Torchwood.

240
00:16:25,439 --> 00:16:30,126
Sorry you've had
a wasted journey, Mr. . .Harker.

241
00:16:30,116 --> 00:16:32,801
Harkness. And it's Captain,
but you can call me Jack.

242
00:16:32,792 --> 00:16:35,477
Captain?
Where did you park your boat?

243
00:16:37,344 --> 00:16:39,187
I like a man with a sense of humour.

244
00:16:39,184 --> 00:16:41,470
Know any good gags
about clinical trials?

245
00:16:41,461 --> 00:16:45,386
Well, Jack, none of these faces
mean anything to me.

246
00:16:45,378 --> 00:16:51,214
And as the institute director,
I would have met them personally,
had they been our trial subjects.

247
00:16:51,212 --> 00:16:54,932
Dr Copley. . . Professor, actually.

248
00:16:56,966 --> 00:16:59,730
But I can call you Aaron, right?

249
00:16:59,723 --> 00:17:02,760
See, this is a little awkward.

250
00:17:02,760 --> 00:17:05,524
Two of these people were murdered.

251
00:17:05,517 --> 00:17:08,441
Another died of a parasitic
infection of alien origin

252
00:17:08,434 --> 00:17:11,915
and one of the victims mentioned
your organisation's name

253
00:17:11,912 --> 00:17:16,076
shortly before she died.
Alien origin? That's preposterous.

254
00:17:16,066 --> 00:17:20,150
Er, Professor,
when I was writing my MD thesis,

255
00:17:20,139 --> 00:17:24,337
your published works on immunology
were very helpful, so thank you.

256
00:17:24,337 --> 00:17:26,020
Glad to be of service.

257
00:17:26,017 --> 00:17:30,056
Now, if there was a drug
that could restore the human body

258
00:17:30,050 --> 00:17:33,770
back to its factory settings,
as it were, you would know about it.

259
00:17:33,768 --> 00:17:35,326
You're right, I would.

260
00:17:35,324 --> 00:17:38,487
But nothing like that exists.

261
00:17:38,482 --> 00:17:41,849
I had a boyfriend whose
nostrils flared when HE was lying.

262
00:17:45,236 --> 00:17:48,433
I'm already late
for my next appointment.

263
00:17:48,432 --> 00:17:50,593
You go ahead.
We'll have a look around.

264
00:17:50,589 --> 00:17:53,831
Well, obviously our research suites
are classified,

265
00:17:53,824 --> 00:17:57,749
so we can't grant you access
to those, but we'd be delighted
to give you the PR tour.

266
00:17:57,741 --> 00:18:00,141
Normally, Aaron,
we go where we like.

267
00:18:00,138 --> 00:18:02,186
Not here, actually.

268
00:18:02,175 --> 00:18:04,063
Ask Whitehall.

269
00:18:04,055 --> 00:18:05,579
We're fireproof.

270
00:18:05,571 --> 00:18:09,814
Yeah. I had a bad experience
with a politician recently.

271
00:18:09,809 --> 00:18:13,097
I tend not to listen
to Whitehall any more.

272
00:18:13,086 --> 00:18:17,125
Let me get someone to guide you
back to your vehicle.

273
00:18:17,120 --> 00:18:19,088
Was it me,
or was he a little touchy?

274
00:18:19,080 --> 00:18:21,560
Yeah, so much for
the polite approach.

275
00:18:21,556 --> 00:18:23,877
We need to turn this place over.

276
00:18:23,874 --> 00:18:26,001
BEEPING
Oh, yeah.

277
00:18:25,991 --> 00:18:31,509
Cos this place has the highest
concentration of alien life forms
this side of the Rift.

278
00:18:33,062 --> 00:18:35,348
Grey is so not her colour.

279
00:18:47,647 --> 00:18:49,251
I can't hack in there, Jack.

280
00:18:49,245 --> 00:18:53,011
And if I keep trying
a brute-force approach,
they'll know they're under attack.

281
00:18:53,005 --> 00:18:56,441
An alien life form is preying
on humans. I need a way in there.

282
00:18:56,438 --> 00:19:01,717
Tosh, I've got the results of that
research. On the screen now.

283
00:19:06,626 --> 00:19:10,869
Ianto, that's brilliant! They're
in the market for volunteers.

284
00:19:10,861 --> 00:19:14,865
That's understandable,
given their wastage rate.
One of us goes in undercover.

285
00:19:14,857 --> 00:19:18,224
No, we don't know enough about it.
Too many things could go wrong.

286
00:19:18,219 --> 00:19:21,734
Unless you put a medic in there.
Someone who knew what to look for.

287
00:19:21,732 --> 00:19:23,734
Yeah, but I can't do it.
They know me now.

288
00:19:23,729 --> 00:19:27,893
I know it's hard to believe, Owen,
but I wasn't thinking of you.

289
00:19:27,886 --> 00:19:29,922
No way.

290
00:19:29,923 --> 00:19:33,324
Come on, Jack, I've been
in worse places and you know it.

291
00:19:44,148 --> 00:19:45,866
OK.

292
00:19:47,862 --> 00:19:49,500
Jack, can I have a word?

293
00:19:49,500 --> 00:19:53,823
I know you're big buddies
from way back whenever, but you
can't just send her in like this.

294
00:19:53,816 --> 00:19:55,704
Trust me. She's more than capable.

295
00:19:55,693 --> 00:19:58,253
I'd rely on Martha
if the world was ending.

296
00:19:58,253 --> 00:20:00,813
In fact, I did.

297
00:20:00,810 --> 00:20:05,372
OK, these are the plans
for the Pharm's buildings.

298
00:20:05,365 --> 00:20:09,165
From what Jack and Owen saw,
they reckon that the main house

299
00:20:09,162 --> 00:20:12,199
contains Copley's office,
medical research suites

300
00:20:12,198 --> 00:20:16,476
and the accommodation
for the clinical trials subjects.
What about the rear buildings?

301
00:20:16,473 --> 00:20:19,317
Restricted area,
fenced off, armed security.

302
00:20:19,313 --> 00:20:23,431
Jack thinks that's where
the readings of alien life
forms came from. Cool.

303
00:20:23,423 --> 00:20:26,460
But you don't need to go anywhere
near there. Spoilsport.

304
00:20:26,461 --> 00:20:31,262
The first thing you need to do
is get yourself accepted
as a clinical trials subject.

305
00:20:31,258 --> 00:20:36,616
Don't try too hard, don't draw
too much attention to yourself.
Be invisible. I can do that.

306
00:20:36,611 --> 00:20:39,933
Once you're in, we need you to gain
access to the Pharm's IT systems,

307
00:20:39,929 --> 00:20:42,966
close down the system firewalls
and security protocols.

308
00:20:42,966 --> 00:20:47,482
Tosh can gain access to the files
and see what they're up to.
Industrial espionage.

309
00:20:47,481 --> 00:20:53,442
It's very civilised. Once you've
done that, get out. Don't take any
unnecessary risks. Understood. Cool.

310
00:20:54,873 --> 00:21:00,425
So, Jack asked me if I could
get you a UNIT cap to wear.

311
00:21:00,426 --> 00:21:04,226
Did he? Well, red is my colour.

312
00:21:04,220 --> 00:21:08,099
So am I right in thinking
that you and he. . . ?

313
00:21:08,100 --> 00:21:11,740
We. . .dabble.

314
00:21:11,732 --> 00:21:14,417
Yeah? Yeah.

315
00:21:14,411 --> 00:21:17,289
So what's his dabbling like?

316
00:21:18,687 --> 00:21:22,009
Innovative. Really?
Bordering on the avant garde.

317
00:21:22,004 --> 00:21:23,926
Wow.

318
00:21:23,921 --> 00:21:26,685
Oh, yeah.

319
00:21:26,679 --> 00:21:30,399
Huh. So shall we get
your cover story sorted? Absolutely.

320
00:21:30,396 --> 00:21:32,125
Fake ID.

321
00:21:32,116 --> 00:21:34,914
First name Samantha.

322
00:21:34,909 --> 00:21:36,718
Thought the Jones would be safe.

323
00:21:36,707 --> 00:21:39,710
OK. How do I stay in touch?
Communication's very tricky.

324
00:21:39,704 --> 00:21:41,342
The whole place could be wired.

325
00:21:41,341 --> 00:21:44,458
We don't want you chattering away
to us and being overheard.

326
00:21:44,458 --> 00:21:47,621
But I want to monitor you
at all times. So?

327
00:21:47,615 --> 00:21:51,176
I don't need contact lenses.
You need these. OK?

328
00:21:54,409 --> 00:21:59,415
Oh, I'm a camera! As Chris Isherwood
once said to me when we were
cruising the Kurfurstendamm.

329
00:21:59,404 --> 00:22:05,718
And we. . .can. . .text.

330
00:22:05,716 --> 00:22:10,005
Wow! Power comes from the body heat,
so they only work
when you're wearing them.

331
00:22:09,994 --> 00:22:14,272
Yeah, so you have to wear them
everywhere. I'll do some things
with my eyes shut, then.

332
00:22:14,265 --> 00:22:16,551
In an emergency,
we can speak directly to you.

333
00:22:16,543 --> 00:22:19,592
The lens will communicate with
your sensory neuroreceptors.

334
00:22:19,583 --> 00:22:21,266
Bypasses the auditory system.

335
00:22:21,260 --> 00:22:23,501
But can't these signals
be intercepted?

336
00:22:23,496 --> 00:22:27,614
Alien technology. Which exploits
a solution to the EPR paradox.

337
00:22:27,614 --> 00:22:31,095
Oh, quantum entanglement
of remote particles. OK, cool.

338
00:22:31,090 --> 00:22:33,376
Did I mention she was brilliant?

339
00:22:34,608 --> 00:22:40,012
It's standard procedure to take
two blood tests. One of them
will be analysed overnight.

340
00:22:40,002 --> 00:22:44,678
Thank you, Nurse. So tell us
the places you've been to, Samantha.

341
00:22:44,677 --> 00:22:50,115
Well, I had a great time
in North America, France
and Germany, Australia. . .

342
00:22:50,111 --> 00:22:52,067
What about the Third World?

343
00:22:52,067 --> 00:22:54,023
Africa, Latin America?

344
00:22:54,023 --> 00:22:57,470
No, but I'm sure
I'll get round to it.

345
00:22:57,461 --> 00:23:00,498
Travel off the beaten track
can be a bit of a problem for us.

346
00:23:00,498 --> 00:23:04,423
If you had some exotic tropical
disease, there could be unexpected
side effects,

347
00:23:04,414 --> 00:23:07,144
and volunteers' welfare
is our absolute priority.

348
00:23:07,134 --> 00:23:11,935
I don't think there'll be any
problem with that. And I'm very
conscious of health issues.

349
00:23:17,124 --> 00:23:19,001
My mum's a nurse.

350
00:23:20,558 --> 00:23:23,163
This is Professor Copley, Samantha.

351
00:23:23,155 --> 00:23:25,510
Institute director.
Hi, Sam. Nice to meet you.

352
00:23:25,508 --> 00:23:28,397
Tell her to get close to Copley.

353
00:23:28,389 --> 00:23:31,074
I see you're a postgraduate
student at the moment.

354
00:23:31,067 --> 00:23:35,185
- That's right.
- Studying what?
- Creative writing.

355
00:23:35,179 --> 00:23:38,307
So I really need the cash.

356
00:23:38,297 --> 00:23:43,143
I'm sure you'll understand,
Samantha, that we have a lot of
applicants. Tell her not to lose him.

357
00:23:43,135 --> 00:23:45,103
We'll let you know in due course.

358
00:23:46,769 --> 00:23:51,775
- Actually, there's something
I should have told you.
- Oh, yes?

359
00:23:53,602 --> 00:23:56,480
It'll show up in
the test results anyway.

360
00:23:58,997 --> 00:24:01,443
I did have a hepatitis infection.

361
00:24:01,437 --> 00:24:05,112
No, no, no, she's bullshitting.
It's her way in.

362
00:24:05,111 --> 00:24:09,389
I mean, I'm fine now,
but it stays in the blood.

363
00:24:09,384 --> 00:24:12,501
Strictly speaking,
it's incurable, right?

364
00:24:12,501 --> 00:24:15,538
That puts a different
complexion on things.

365
00:24:15,539 --> 00:24:17,495
We could use a
subject with hepatitis.

366
00:24:17,495 --> 00:24:19,975
- Are you available
to start right now?
- Well, sure.

367
00:24:19,973 --> 00:24:21,941
I've brought my overnight things.

368
00:24:21,933 --> 00:24:25,608
Then all we need is your signature
on this confidentiality agreement.

369
00:24:25,607 --> 00:24:28,053
She's in.

370
00:24:28,047 --> 00:24:32,848
As Chris Isherwood also said,
it's not the getting in,
it's the getting out.

371
00:24:34,438 --> 00:24:37,202
- Thank you.
- What sort of drugs
will you want me to take?

372
00:24:37,197 --> 00:24:40,041
We have got various products
at the clinical trials stage.

373
00:24:40,032 --> 00:24:42,830
You'll be given a briefing
once we've finalised the programme,

374
00:24:42,828 --> 00:24:46,867
and of course we won't proceed
unless we have your informed consent.

375
00:24:52,020 --> 00:24:53,783
Come on, Martha.

376
00:24:55,374 --> 00:24:58,025
Let her settle in.
It's gonna be a long night ahead.

377
00:25:04,846 --> 00:25:09,772
You and Martha are getting on well.
Yeah, you know me - Mr Sociable.

378
00:25:09,762 --> 00:25:13,084
She's beautiful. Is she?

379
00:25:15,251 --> 00:25:18,379
You know she is.
Yes, well, fair cop.

380
00:25:18,371 --> 00:25:20,692
And a doctor.

381
00:25:20,688 --> 00:25:23,725
Perfect match.
No, she's only interested in work.

382
00:25:23,724 --> 00:25:27,842
Do you think? Yeah, a bit of
flirting so I'll show her the ropes.

383
00:25:27,839 --> 00:25:32,606
Plus, if I tried anything with her,
I think Jack would have my kneecaps.

384
00:25:33,635 --> 00:25:39,278
What happened
to that, um, pool tournament
you were organising? That?

385
00:25:39,269 --> 00:25:41,749
It was never a tournament.

386
00:25:41,747 --> 00:25:46,423
What was all that about, then?
It was supposed to be a date. Sorry?

387
00:25:46,421 --> 00:25:48,582
I was asking you out on a date.

388
00:25:48,578 --> 00:25:51,183
A date?

389
00:25:51,179 --> 00:25:53,500
You didn't realise? You and me?

390
00:25:53,493 --> 00:25:55,700
Yeah.

391
00:25:55,689 --> 00:26:01,252
I see. And. . .you still want that?
Yeah.

392
00:26:01,242 --> 00:26:03,051
Right.

393
00:26:03,042 --> 00:26:08,048
I just thought if we spent
some time together, an evening. . .

394
00:26:08,037 --> 00:26:09,561
All right.

395
00:26:09,555 --> 00:26:11,955
Sorry?

396
00:26:11,955 --> 00:26:14,162
Just do it. Are you being sarcastic?

397
00:26:14,151 --> 00:26:16,278
No.

398
00:26:16,269 --> 00:26:19,750
You're being polite. You'll stand me
up. I've just said yes, haven't I?

399
00:26:19,746 --> 00:26:22,306
One date, see how it goes,
which might be nowhere.

400
00:26:22,302 --> 00:26:25,510
That's fine. A drink. OK. Yeah.

401
00:26:25,500 --> 00:26:27,866
I'm going to keep
flirting with people, OK?

402
00:26:27,856 --> 00:26:32,213
Just cos of this, doesn't mean
I'm going to stop flirting.
You can be king of flirts. OK.

403
00:26:32,210 --> 00:26:33,689
Right, then.

404
00:26:34,728 --> 00:26:36,013
Yeah.

405
00:26:36,008 --> 00:26:39,603
Good. We should, er. . .
concentrate on Martha.

406
00:26:40,642 --> 00:26:42,166
Yeah.

407
00:27:42,659 --> 00:27:46,572
Tosh, can you get us past this?
Easy peasy.

408
00:27:46,572 --> 00:27:50,451
She just needs to get the
lenses to within the EPR field.

409
00:28:48,909 --> 00:28:51,673
Tosh, can you help her blag her
way into the computer system?

410
00:28:51,667 --> 00:28:56,309
It'll take time to talk
her through it. We don't have time.
I want her out of that office.

411
00:28:56,299 --> 00:29:00,463
Well, if I can get her to give me
remote control of the computer. . .

412
00:29:25,150 --> 00:29:27,755
. .I have control.

413
00:29:34,901 --> 00:29:37,745
The life cycle of the parasite.

414
00:29:37,736 --> 00:29:40,534
They call it the Mayfly. Wow.

415
00:29:42,529 --> 00:29:46,613
We've never seen a species
like that before. It's beautiful.

416
00:29:46,606 --> 00:29:50,372
It's lethal.
But what is Copley doing with them?

417
00:29:50,364 --> 00:29:55,358
Martha, now we've got control,
we can go through all of this here.
Get out of there pronto.

418
00:30:02,391 --> 00:30:06,509
Do you have that code-breaker
software? I'm sending the patch now.
Thank you.

419
00:30:18,651 --> 00:30:22,337
'Break out in Zone A.
All return to Zone A immediately.

420
00:30:22,327 --> 00:30:25,171
'Breakout in Zone A.
Break out in Zone A.'

421
00:30:25,165 --> 00:30:26,928
ALARM RINGS

422
00:30:28,801 --> 00:30:31,486
'All patrols proceed
with extreme caution.

423
00:30:31,479 --> 00:30:34,118
'The escaped creature
is extremely dangerous.'

424
00:30:46,862 --> 00:30:52,107
Jack? I've got the list of the
clinical trials subjects here.

425
00:30:52,098 --> 00:30:54,134
Meredith Roberts,
Marie Thomas, Barry Leonard.

426
00:30:54,132 --> 00:30:55,929
All the murder victims.

427
00:30:55,928 --> 00:30:58,453
Ooh, who's BD?

428
00:30:59,526 --> 00:31:05,681
Executive actions?

429
00:31:05,681 --> 00:31:07,967
The Pharm are running
their own hit man,

430
00:31:07,957 --> 00:31:10,357
which is unusual
for a medical research facility.

431
00:31:10,355 --> 00:31:13,438
Wait, there's a name here
that we haven't seen before.

432
00:31:13,433 --> 00:31:16,834
Elin Morgan? She hasn't been
reported missing or dead.

433
00:31:16,829 --> 00:31:19,115
She soon will be.
Take Ianto and pull her in.

434
00:31:19,107 --> 00:31:21,507
ALARM RINGS

435
00:31:36,768 --> 00:31:38,611
APPROACHING VOICES

436
00:31:42,481 --> 00:31:45,291
'Do not attempt to approach
the creature, is that understood?

437
00:31:45,280 --> 00:31:47,726
'Stun and sedate only,
the creature is highly dangerous.'

438
00:31:47,716 --> 00:31:49,513
Understood. Come on, keep moving!

439
00:31:53,231 --> 00:31:58,669
If the Pharm have their own hit man,
God knows what they're capable of.
Yeah, and I put her in there.

440
00:32:02,303 --> 00:32:05,056
WHISTLE BLOWS

441
00:32:05,055 --> 00:32:07,501
EERIE WARBLING

442
00:32:10,889 --> 00:32:14,973
Shit! What was that? Radiation
surge? We've lost her signal!

443
00:32:14,967 --> 00:32:16,923
Agh! Ah!

444
00:32:18,802 --> 00:32:21,282
EERIE WARBLING CONTINUES

445
00:32:28,154 --> 00:32:30,042
Agh!

446
00:32:30,032 --> 00:32:31,636
There it is!

447
00:32:31,628 --> 00:32:34,472
Call patrol. Creature located.

448
00:32:41,817 --> 00:32:43,899
I can't get her back.

449
00:32:43,893 --> 00:32:47,420
We have to get her out of there.
That place is swamped in security.

450
00:32:47,411 --> 00:32:51,086
If we steam in, we'll be putting her
at risk! We can't leave her there.

451
00:32:51,085 --> 00:32:55,408
If I can't get her signal in 30
minutes, we think of alternatives.
Anything could be happening to her.

452
00:32:55,401 --> 00:32:59,963
Martha can handle herself.
She's been in worse situations
than this. Sure about that?

453
00:33:02,315 --> 00:33:08,311
What's that? Billy Davis' mobile.
He'll be at Elin's flat
in three minutes.

454
00:33:26,769 --> 00:33:29,374
Hands above your head! Up!

455
00:33:36,001 --> 00:33:40,597
Jack, we've got Billy Davis. He
could help get you into the Pharm.

456
00:33:42,592 --> 00:33:47,347
Will you tell this gorilla to
let me go? ! What is going on? !

457
00:33:47,348 --> 00:33:50,988
- Good work.

458
00:33:50,986 --> 00:33:54,228
- You can't treat me like this!
- You lied to us, Samantha.

459
00:33:54,218 --> 00:33:57,699
Can I just explain? I got bored stuck
in that room, so I went for a walk,

460
00:33:57,698 --> 00:34:01,259
and first that thing attacked me,
and then your heavies assaulted me.

461
00:34:01,253 --> 00:34:03,892
You don't owe any
loyalty to Torchwood.

462
00:34:03,888 --> 00:34:10,202
- Jack Harkness has treated you
in a criminally irresponsible way.
- Who? I really don't understand!

463
00:34:10,202 --> 00:34:12,807
Don't bother.
This is not an interrogation.

464
00:34:12,799 --> 00:34:15,882
Torchwood is irrelevant to us,
not even a nuisance.

465
00:34:15,879 --> 00:34:19,713
In fact, they've done us
quite a favour putting you in here.

466
00:34:19,712 --> 00:34:23,796
We've analysed your test results -
you really are something special.

467
00:34:24,950 --> 00:34:26,429
Agh!

468
00:34:26,428 --> 00:34:33,300
I got terrible guts, dunno what
it is. Bad conscience, Billy.
Try confessing. Get stuffed.

469
00:34:33,298 --> 00:34:36,461
OK, let's do it the hard way.

470
00:34:36,456 --> 00:34:39,334
CREATURE GROWLS
Merciful Christ! What the. . . ?

471
00:34:42,409 --> 00:34:44,377
Agh-hhh!
CREATURE ROARS

472
00:34:44,366 --> 00:34:46,049
They have a tendency to act up.

473
00:34:46,046 --> 00:34:48,492
Losing him! Please!
Something to say, Billy?

474
00:34:48,484 --> 00:34:52,636
Yeah, yeah, whatever you want, just
get it away from me! Get it off me!

475
00:34:56,195 --> 00:34:58,880
OK, Billy, you've been
on a killing spree, why?

476
00:34:58,871 --> 00:35:00,589
I work for the Pharm!

477
00:35:00,589 --> 00:35:02,750
They'd been giving people
this Reset drug.

478
00:35:02,749 --> 00:35:06,025
But there were these side effects -
parasites or something.

479
00:35:06,025 --> 00:35:10,906
They were gonna die anyway, so I had
to get rid of them before any weird
symptoms showed up. . .in public.

480
00:35:10,897 --> 00:35:13,457
Do you know what lymphocytes are,
Samantha?

481
00:35:13,454 --> 00:35:16,537
A kind of white blood cell,
part of the immune system.

482
00:35:16,531 --> 00:35:20,729
Well, your lymphocytes are really
quite extraordinary.

483
00:35:20,728 --> 00:35:25,609
We've never seen anything like
them before, not in a human being.
Aliens are a different matter.

484
00:35:25,602 --> 00:35:28,446
Aliens? I don't know
what you're talking about.

485
00:35:28,440 --> 00:35:30,761
Your lymphocytes and God knows
what other cells have mutated.

486
00:35:30,756 --> 00:35:33,725
- Mutated? How?
- Under the influence of radiation.

487
00:35:33,716 --> 00:35:37,994
Radiation
that's not found in the temporally
stable environments on Earth.

488
00:35:37,989 --> 00:35:39,638
I don't know what that means.

489
00:35:39,628 --> 00:35:45,578
We've dealt with aliens before,
but we have never come across
anything as exotic as you.

490
00:35:45,578 --> 00:35:49,025
A human being who's
travelled in time and space.

491
00:35:49,018 --> 00:35:52,454
Tell me about it.
How is that possible?

492
00:35:52,451 --> 00:35:55,739
What did you see out there?

493
00:35:55,729 --> 00:35:57,367
This is mad.

494
00:35:57,367 --> 00:35:59,847
I don't know what you mean.

495
00:35:59,846 --> 00:36:02,644
Fine. If that's the
way you want to play it.

496
00:36:02,643 --> 00:36:08,320
However it happened, it means you
have a uniquely effective immune
system, which is what we need.

497
00:36:08,318 --> 00:36:11,196
We're developing a drug that's
going to change the world, Sam.

498
00:36:11,194 --> 00:36:16,075
Incurable cancers, AIDS - all the
scourges of the human race wiped out.

499
00:36:16,069 --> 00:36:19,197
A revolution in medicine
and social welfare.

500
00:36:19,189 --> 00:36:20,986
Except it's still imperfect.

501
00:36:20,986 --> 00:36:26,947
I'd like to know what your funky
lymphatic system makes of
those imperfections.

502
00:36:26,937 --> 00:36:29,337
I am not taking that!

503
00:36:29,333 --> 00:36:31,733
But you volunteered.

504
00:36:36,568 --> 00:36:41,164
OK, we're going into the Pharm
and you're going to front it.
Yeah, yeah. OK.

505
00:36:41,161 --> 00:36:45,450
My stomach! My stomach!
My stomach! Agh!

506
00:36:47,396 --> 00:36:52,311
Agh! Whoa!
Owen, we need him alive! Yeah, all
right, I'm flying blind here, Jack!

507
00:36:52,310 --> 00:36:55,871
Do something! Let's start with this.

508
00:37:01,424 --> 00:37:06,339
I think I've got it, OK?
I've got the calibrations right.
I can get it out of him.

509
00:37:07,775 --> 00:37:13,771
Whoa! God! Owen, deal with it.
Are you sure you had
those calibrations right?

510
00:37:13,765 --> 00:37:15,653
I'm sorry, all right?

511
00:37:18,043 --> 00:37:23,925
He must have breathed in larva
when one of his victims died.
This could have been me, or Martha.

512
00:37:27,152 --> 00:37:31,589
I've given her twice
the critical dose.
So, Mayfly larvae are incubating?

513
00:37:31,588 --> 00:37:36,036
Are you sure about this? Her
immune system's clearly reacting.

514
00:37:36,026 --> 00:37:38,221
There's obviously
quite a fight going on inside her.

515
00:37:38,219 --> 00:37:41,700
Keep your nerve.
We're making history.

516
00:37:45,331 --> 00:37:47,856
Ianto, what have you done
with Billy Davis' body?

517
00:37:47,851 --> 00:37:51,412
Um, I was just about to
dispose of it. Why?

518
00:37:51,405 --> 00:37:54,488
I've thought of a way we can
use him to get us into the Pharm.

519
00:37:56,602 --> 00:37:58,285
Clever, huh?

520
00:37:58,279 --> 00:38:02,887
Oh, you are warped on the inside.
How do you think of these things?

521
00:38:02,877 --> 00:38:05,596
I'll take that as a compliment.

522
00:38:42,472 --> 00:38:44,997
Tosh, Gwen, Ianto, check out Zone A.

523
00:38:44,992 --> 00:38:46,994
We're going after Martha. Let's go!

524
00:39:06,208 --> 00:39:08,369
Hands above your head!

525
00:39:08,364 --> 00:39:11,083
What have you done to her?

526
00:39:11,081 --> 00:39:16,804
Tell me that's not Reset!
She's survived the larval stage,
the only subject ever to do so.

527
00:39:16,796 --> 00:39:20,755
Fascinating. Turns out these
bugs practice sibling cannibalism.

528
00:39:20,753 --> 00:39:24,428
Only the strongest individual is left
now. God knows what happens next.

529
00:39:24,427 --> 00:39:26,668
Put a stop to this! I can't.

530
00:39:26,667 --> 00:39:28,828
I don't know how.

531
00:39:52,080 --> 00:39:54,162
Put your hands above your head!

532
00:40:00,349 --> 00:40:02,158
Ianto.

533
00:40:03,186 --> 00:40:05,393
Bloody hell.

534
00:40:07,700 --> 00:40:11,420
Jack, this thing's killing her.
I don't know what I can do.

535
00:40:11,417 --> 00:40:14,181
Owen, stay calm,
there has gotta be something.

536
00:40:23,404 --> 00:40:26,692
What's happening here?
This is what the Pharm is all about.

537
00:40:26,681 --> 00:40:29,969
We farm captive aliens
for the exotic chemical
products they metabolise.

538
00:40:29,958 --> 00:40:35,521
What the hell do you get from
a weevil? Some pesticides, and a
quite powerful chemical defoliant.

539
00:40:35,513 --> 00:40:39,153
But the weevils aren't what's
going to clinch the Nobel for us.

540
00:40:39,150 --> 00:40:42,745
The Mayfly, our feedstock for Reset.

541
00:40:42,741 --> 00:40:47,587
Given time, we'll tweak the
product for human use, and then
it'll be bigger than penicillin.

542
00:40:54,012 --> 00:40:56,060
Jack, I can give you
a report on Zone A.

543
00:40:56,049 --> 00:41:00,292
They're holding dozens
of creatures. They seem to be
using them as test subjects.

544
00:41:14,792 --> 00:41:17,750
Understood, Ianto.
Tell Tosh to go for total shutdown.

545
00:41:19,342 --> 00:41:24,109
This place is a torture chamber.
I don't need to debate
medical ethics with you.

546
00:41:24,100 --> 00:41:28,059
You abused the Mayflies,
you turned them into parasites!

547
00:41:28,053 --> 00:41:30,817
We didn't understand how
the Mayflies reproduced.

548
00:41:30,814 --> 00:41:32,770
We tried to limit the damage.

549
00:41:32,771 --> 00:41:35,615
What, by murdering people?
They were going to die anyway.

550
00:41:35,608 --> 00:41:39,487
We're on the edge of
the greatest discovery in history.
It has to be worth a few sacrifices!

551
00:41:39,482 --> 00:41:42,292
You must understand that, Jack,
you're involved in alien research.

552
00:41:42,282 --> 00:41:43,362
Not like this.

553
00:41:48,076 --> 00:41:54,436
I'm closing this place down.
In your dreams. This is a state
of the art, official facility.

554
00:41:54,427 --> 00:41:56,987
Oh, I'm not going to
do it by sending a memo.

555
00:41:56,984 --> 00:42:00,101
We're in control of your IT systems.

556
00:42:00,101 --> 00:42:04,140
As we speak, we're crashing your
data banks, wiping your records.

557
00:42:04,136 --> 00:42:07,025
That's cyber terrorism!
And that'sjust for starters.

558
00:42:07,016 --> 00:42:13,057
We're going to trip the systems
of your fire, radiation and
biohazard safety networks.

559
00:42:13,046 --> 00:42:15,207
The power will be cut,
sprinklers will be activated,

560
00:42:15,207 --> 00:42:21,567
and a large part of this facility
will be sealed and flooded with
inert gases. The aliens will die.

561
00:42:21,558 --> 00:42:24,243
They're already dying. This way
they'll be put out of their misery.

562
00:42:24,237 --> 00:42:25,966
For God's sake,
we're on the same side!

563
00:42:25,957 --> 00:42:32,157
No. Combating hostile aliens
is one thing, but this is slavery,
exploitation, a war crime!

564
00:42:32,147 --> 00:42:34,468
Jack, I need your help!

565
00:42:35,462 --> 00:42:38,989
What the hell are you doing? !
This is the only way
we'll save Martha.

566
00:42:38,979 --> 00:42:43,780
I think I understand how it works.
You'd better be sure
because it's never worked before.

567
00:42:43,774 --> 00:42:48,814
Owen, are you sure it's safe? OK,
Jack! Owen, tell me you're sure!

568
00:42:48,811 --> 00:42:52,645
You could kill her with that thing!
We're losing her!

569
00:42:53,644 --> 00:42:55,532
Ah!

570
00:43:00,399 --> 00:43:03,960
A SINGLE TONE BLEEPS
What have you done?

571
00:43:10,943 --> 00:43:13,343
Oh, bloody hell, it worked.
Thank God for that.

572
00:43:13,341 --> 00:43:15,263
Let's get her out of here.

573
00:43:21,375 --> 00:43:24,981
I am prescribing rest and
recuperation for you, madam,

574
00:43:24,972 --> 00:43:29,727
and a few days in bed,
preferably under my supervision.

575
00:43:29,726 --> 00:43:32,809
Owen, I don't know how to break
this to you - I've got a boyfriend.

576
00:43:32,803 --> 00:43:36,239
Yeah, but has he saved your life
like I did?

577
00:43:36,238 --> 00:43:39,446
Um, yes, actually.

578
00:43:39,437 --> 00:43:41,280
Oh.

579
00:43:41,277 --> 00:43:43,996
Arms up on there.

580
00:43:43,990 --> 00:43:45,992
Do it.

581
00:43:45,988 --> 00:43:50,869
'Facility shut down programme. All
personnel must evacuate immediately.

582
00:43:50,862 --> 00:43:53,467
'Facility shut down programme.

583
00:43:53,460 --> 00:43:56,145
'All personnel must
evacuate immediately.'

584
00:43:56,137 --> 00:43:58,423
OK, let's go!

585
00:43:58,414 --> 00:44:02,578
Did you really think I was
going to let you just walk away?

586
00:44:02,571 --> 00:44:07,645
You've ruined everything I've worked
for. Now, let's not be stupid. OK?

587
00:44:07,645 --> 00:44:11,809
We're both rational men, scientists.

588
00:44:15,636 --> 00:44:18,924
I know you don't want to shoot.

589
00:44:23,109 --> 00:44:25,384
You're next!

590
00:44:28,541 --> 00:44:31,146
Owen! Can you hear me, Owen? !

591
00:44:31,138 --> 00:44:33,584
You've got to help him!
Owen, stay with me. Owen.

592
00:44:33,578 --> 00:44:36,138
Owen, look at me, look at me.
Owen, look right at me.

593
00:44:36,135 --> 00:44:40,174
Stay with me, Owen, stay with me.
Stay with me, buddy. Come on.

594
00:44:41,969 --> 00:44:43,607
Owen, speak to me!

595
00:44:57,272 --> 00:44:59,035
He's dead.

596
00:45:05,503 --> 00:45:07,459
Owen. . .

597
00:45:22,566 --> 00:45:25,285
The time is 21.30.

598
00:45:25,282 --> 00:45:27,284
Autopsy on Owen Harper.

599
00:45:27,280 --> 00:45:29,601
Torchwood officer 565.

600
00:45:29,598 --> 00:45:31,964
Aged 27.

601
00:45:31,956 --> 00:45:34,754
Autopsy begins.

602
00:45:34,753 --> 00:45:37,472
The energy just went off the scale.

603
00:45:37,470 --> 00:45:39,745
Can you see where it is?

604
00:45:39,744 --> 00:45:42,144
You can't use it.
Who knows what'll happen!

605
00:45:42,144 --> 00:45:44,226
I was hoping for a miracle.

606
00:45:44,221 --> 00:45:46,781
Where did he go? It's here. Martha!

607
00:45:46,777 --> 00:45:50,895
It must be death,
because it's stolen my life.



